========================================================================
WHAT THIS PROVES · WHAT IT DOESN'T
========================================================================

PROVEN:
  · alphabet versions can be tracked with biological metadata (parent,
    mutation reason, fitness, problems-solved, born-at)
  · selection pressure — different problems demand different primitives
    — drives directed extensions to the language
  · NOT all problems require evolution: max(7,3) was solved by the founder
    using existing cmp+branch — that's DNA-expressible without language change
  · crossover produces children with union-of-parents primitives — the
    species can recombine capabilities discovered along separate lineages
  · phylogeny is a real tree, content-addressed at every node

NOT PROVEN (still v1+):
  · automated capability inference — the missing-primitive proposal here
    is hand-written. real biology mutates randomly; real engineering needs
    type-gap analysis to derive the minimal extension.
  · parsimony pressure — successful lineages should prune unused primitives
    over time. this run only adds, never subtracts.
  · real IPFS pinning — alphabets here are dict-stored. real pinning makes
    the lineage globally pullable by CID, distributable across reasoners.
  · cross-language transpilation — these specimens still execute in the
    shape-VM. v1 of the bridge layer transpiles to JS for outer-shell tests.

THE ORIENTATION:
  latin shape-language is HALF the journey because its grammar is closed,
  its primitives are deterministic, its compositions are typed. the OTHER
  half — heritability, variation, selection, replication, speciation,
  death — is what we just demonstrated mechanically. the language is
  starting to behave like a species. that's the product Dan asked for.

